args:
The party arrives in Hethiwood—the village
from which all the citizens disappeared—and
find evidence of a suspicious ritual led by
none other than Nyarlathotep. With this new
information in hand, they rush back to the
library to confirm their suspicions.
Back from the library, Curran?\nWhat about Heinwald?
Still surrounded by mountains of books.\nI just came here to let off a little steam.
Maybe we should have helped him\nout a little more...
Your giving us rooms in the castle is\nhelp enough. Plus, you're all lending\na hand with Lathna.
It seems like she's slowly getting better,\nwhich is a huge relief.

All thanks to you letting her stay here,
where she's surrounded by friendly people.
Frankly, I don't think I could have helped
her on my own.
From what I gather, she's been having the\nsame exact dream every night. In it,\nshe's chased by the villagers until...
Dream or not, that just isn't right.
I don't think this is an ordinary nightmare.

Hmm... Actually, I remember Heinwald 
saying something about disturbances in
mana having an effect on dreams.
We should go ask him about this.
Look, I get that he's a bit creepy,\nbut he's not THAT bad of a guy.\nPlus, his talents are legit.
Okay, okay. We'll come up with some\nother plan. Black shadows... It can't be...
I have...to go back...to the village.
Hey, if you think it'll help, I'll take you\nback to the village.
Kids have to fellow their dreams, after all!
So this is Hethiwood, the village where\neveryone vanished in a single night...
It sounds scary when you put it like that,\nand yet it looks so...ordinary.

Yes, yes, quite fascinating. Now then, what
exactly is the purpose of our coming here?
Surely it would be more beneficial to
continue our investigation in the library?
It's the first rule of an investigation:\nWhen you're stuck, go back to the \nscene of the original crime!
Bah. You should have just come here\non your own and left me be.
You think I could leave you on your own?\nI know you're up to something in that\nlibrary that you're not telling us about.
You speak as if I am plotting mischief.\nI am interested where this conclusion\nof yours is coming from.
Quit bellyaching and let's look for clues.
For a long time, this village didn't have\na place of worship, but eventually the\nChurch dispatched a priest here.

If the villagers were worshiping something
other than the goddess, it means that
priest would have been seen as the
heretic, and not the other way around.

In other words, there could be information
here that cannot be found elsewhere.
Oh, I do love it when you finally bring
something to the table, Curran.
Quit running your mouth and let's\nstart looking around already!
You say that as if it is an easy thing,\nyet we know not what we are even\nlooking FOR.
At times like this, you have to think from\nthe perspective of whoever might be\ntrying to hide something.
The priest was trying to suss out what the\npeople here believed in—and he didn't\nwant them to know about it.
For if he was discovered, there would be\nno one here to protect him.
So even if he DID know something,\nhe would have kept it hidden.
Well, if I was that priest, I'd hide my\nevidence in a place the villagers\nwould be likely to avoid.
So maybe if we just... Ah ha!
What lies beyond must be important\nindeed if he went to so much trouble\nto disguise it.
In any case, let's head inside.
By the Goddess, look at it...\nWhat a horrible way to die.
It's like he was torn apart...\nWhat could have done this?
For now, let us bury this poor man.\nThen we can search the house.
We will go room by room and see if we\ncan't figure out what happened here.
...Now we'll hopefully be able\nto find something.
This place isn't that big.\nIf we all split up, we—
I'd normally frown on rummaging through\na man's private thoughts, but I don't think\nwe have a choice in this case.

Day 13, First Month of the Dragon:
Some time has passed since my
appointment here to spread the
teachings of the Goddess Ilia.

The fruits of my labor are not sweet,
for these people seem to worship
something that is not our Goddess.
I can only pray it is not some
nefarious evil.

Day 25, Month of the Lovely Dragon:
The villagers and I recently learned
that an inquisitor has been sent here.
They are most displeased by this.

It is no wonder those who do not
carry the teachings of Ilia in their
hearts would be frightened by this,
for an inquisitor's questioning can at
times be quite severe.

The villagers tell me they are praying
for salvation. And yet, I know not to
who—or what—these prayers are
being offered.

Day 28, Month of the Lovely Dragon:
I hear the villagers outside my home.
They are chanting mad gibberish
to the night sky.

I know not if it is merely a strange
language, or some fell magic, but
it is most deeply disquieting. Indeed,
there can be little doubt that I am
the heretic here—not they.

Day 5, Month of the Wardragon
The villagers say something called
the Emissary has appeared, and that
the ritual will begin and salvation
will come.
But there was no way I could believe\nthat dark, disturbing being was an\nEmissary of salvation.

Yet if I give voice to this, I will
be driven hence by the villagers
and slain!
O, Goddess! Pray deliver me!
...Goddess help me, I saw it.\nTheir ＂ritual.＂ Their ＂salvation.＂

Lies! Such a thing could never be
salvation. Caught by a great power
and locked away, they transform
from human to something...not.
Lies. Humans. Warped. Twisting.\nBlack. Nightmare. Chaos.\nIt comes. It comes. IT COMES!
IT COMES IT COMES IT COMES\nTHE EMISSARY COMES FOR THEE
N Y A R L A T H O T E P COMES!
I KNEW he was plotting something!
But he has been trapped within the library\nfor as long as it has been sealed, yes?
Then who could the Nyarlathotep in the\ndiary be? I can't imagine there are TWO\nbeings with that name.
We might be able to figure something\nout if we go ask the Nyarlathotep who\nlives in the Library Obscura.
Then let's hurry back and put\nthe question to him.
If we're going that far, I'd like to also try\ngathering some more information.
Whatever you need to do.\nLet's just hurry!
